and therefore the unlearned learn and not the wise.

Then the unlearned learn1, and not the wise, Cleinias, as you imagine.
At these words the followers of Euthydemus, of whom I spoke, like a chorus at the bidding of their director, laughed and cheered. Then, before the youth had time to recover his breath, Dionysodorus cleverly took him in hand, and said: Yes, Cleinias;

He asked what was the meaning of this, and I replied: Surely wisdom is good–fortune; even a child may know that.

The fortunate are only the wise under another name.

The simple–minded youth was amazed;

If you know, you are knowing.
Certainly, of the knowledge which I have.
That makes no difference;

The speaker may be silent or may speak, or both.

But if speaking things are included in all things, then the speaking are silent.
What, said Ctesippus;
